\begin{verbatim}
poles_extraction(prob::EMAProblem, alg; width, min_prom, max_prom, pks_indices, scaling)
poles_extraction(prob::EMAProblem, order, alg; stabdiag)
\end{verbatim}
Extract poles using Sdof or Mdof experimental modal analysis methods

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob::EMAProblem} or \texttt{prob::MdofProblem}: EMA problem containing FRF data and frequency vector


\item \texttt{order}: Order of the model (only for Mdof methods)


\item \texttt{alg}: Algorithm to extract the poles

\begin{itemize}
\item Sdof methods:

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{PeakPicking}: Peak picking method (default for Sdof methods)


\item \texttt{CircleFit}: Circle fitting method


\item \texttt{LSFit}: Least squares fitting method

\end{itemize}

\item Mdof methods:

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{LSCF}: Least Squares Complex Frequency method (default for Mdof methods)


\item \texttt{PLSCF}: Polyreference Least Squares Complex Frequency method


\item \texttt{LSCE}: Least Squares Complex Exponential method (only for Mdof methods)

\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{stabdiag::Bool}: Boolean to indicate the function is used to build a stability diagram (Only for Mdof methods, default: false)


\item \texttt{width::Int}: Half-width of the peaks (only for Sdof methods, default: 1)


\item \texttt{min\_prom::Real}: Minimum peak prominence (only for Sdof methods, default: 0. dB)


\item \texttt{max\_prom::Real}: Maximum peak prominence (only for Sdof methods, default: Inf)


\item \texttt{pks\_indices::Vector\{Int\}}: Indices of peaks to consider (only for Sdof methods, default: empty vector)

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Outputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{poles}: Vector of extracted complex poles

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Note}

\begin{itemize}
\item For Sdof methods, the natural frequencies and damping ratios are extracted from each FRF (each row of the matrix) and then averaged. The number of FRF used for averaging are those having the maximum (and same) number of peaks detected.

\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
modeshape_extraction(prob, poles, alg; dpi)
modeshape_extraction(residues, poles, alg; dpi, modetype)
\end{verbatim}
Extract mode shapes using Sdof approximation

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{prob::EMAProblem}: EMA problem containing FRF data and frequency vector


\item \texttt{poles}: Vector of complex poles


\item \texttt{alg::SdofModalExtraction} or \texttt{alg::MdofEMA}: Modal extraction algorithm


\item \texttt{dpi}: Driving point indices - default = [1, 1]

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{dpi[1]}: Driving point index on the measurement mesh


\item \texttt{dpi[2]}: Driving point index on the excitation mesh

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{modetype}: Type of mode shape (only for Mdof methods)

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{:emac}: EMA - Complex mode shapes (default)


\item \texttt{:emar}: EMA - Real mode shapes


\item \texttt{:oma}: OMA

\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Output}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{ms}: Mode shapes


\item \texttt{ci}: Scaling factors vector (only for Mdof methods)

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Note}

\begin{itemize}
\item If the number of measurement points is less than the number of excitation points, the mode shapes are estimated at the excitation points (roving hammer test). Otherwise, the mode shapes are estimated at the measurement points (roving accelerometer test).


\item The \texttt{alg} argument is here for performing multiple dispatch but is not used in the function.

\end{itemize}
\textbf{References} [1] M. Géradin and D. J. Rixen. "Mechanical Vibrations: Theory and Application to Structural Dynamics". 3rd. Edition, Wiley, 2015.

[2] C. Ranieri and G. Fabbrocino. "Operational Modal Analysis of Civil Engineering Structures: An Introduction and Guide for Applications". Springer, 2014.

